What is GraphQL?

GraphQL is a query language and runtime for APIs developed by Facebook in 2015. It allows clients to request exactly the data they need—nothing more, nothing less.

Unlike REST (multiple endpoints), GraphQL typically exposes a single endpoint and lets clients specify the structure of the response.


---

1️⃣ Core Concepts of GraphQL


---

1. Schema

The schema defines:

What data is available

The types of data

What queries/mutations can be performed


Example Schema

type User {
  id: ID!
  name: String!
  email: String!
  age: Int
}

type Query {
  getUser(id: ID!): User
  getUsers: [User]
}

type Mutation {
  createUser(name: String!, email: String!, age: Int): User
}

Explanation:

ID! → Non-nullable ID

String! → Required string

[User] → List of users

Query → Read operations

Mutation → Write operations



---

2️⃣ Types

GraphQL has built-in scalar types:

Type	Description

Int	Integer
Float	Decimal
String	Text
Boolean	True/False
ID	Unique identifier


You can also create:

Object types

Input types

Enums

Interfaces

Unions



---

3️⃣ Queries (Read Data)

Queries are used to fetch data.

Basic Query Syntax

query {
  getUser(id: "1") {
    id
    name
    email
  }
}

Response

{
  "data": {
    "getUser": {
      "id": "1",
      "name": "John",
      "email": "john@email.com"
    }
  }
}

Key Concept:

Client chooses fields → Server returns exactly those fields.


---

4️⃣ Arguments

You can pass arguments inside queries.

query {
  getUser(id: "1") {
    name
  }
}


---

5️⃣ Aliases

Used when fetching the same field multiple times.

query {
  userOne: getUser(id: "1") {
    name
  }
  userTwo: getUser(id: "2") {
    name
  }
}


---

6️⃣ Variables

Instead of hardcoding values:

query GetUser($userId: ID!) {
  getUser(id: $userId) {
    name
    email
  }
}

JSON Variables

{
  "userId": "1"
}


---

7️⃣ Mutations (Write Data)

Used to create, update, or delete data.

Mutation Syntax

mutation {
  createUser(name: "Alice", email: "alice@email.com", age: 25) {
    id
    name
  }
}

Response

{
  "data": {
    "createUser": {
      "id": "3",
      "name": "Alice"
    }
  }
}


---

8️⃣ Input Types

Used to send structured data.

Schema

input CreateUserInput {
  name: String!
  email: String!
  age: Int
}

type Mutation {
  createUser(input: CreateUserInput!): User
}

Mutation

mutation {
  createUser(input: {
    name: "Bob",
    email: "bob@email.com",
    age: 30
  }) {
    id
    name
  }
}


---

9️⃣ Nested Queries

GraphQL allows fetching related data in one request.

Schema

type Post {
  id: ID!
  title: String!
  author: User
}

Query

query {
  getUser(id: "1") {
    name
    posts {
      title
    }
  }
}


