1️⃣ Fragments (Reusable Query Parts)

Fragments allow you to reuse field selections across queries.

Example Schema

type User {
  id: ID!
  name: String!
  email: String!
  age: Int
}

Without Fragment

query {
  getUser(id: "1") {
    id
    name
    email
  }
  getUsers {
    id
    name
    email
  }
}

With Fragment

fragment UserFields on User {
  id
  name
  email
}

query {
  getUser(id: "1") {
    ...UserFields
  }
  getUsers {
    ...UserFields
  }
}

Why Important?

Reduces duplication

Cleaner large-scale frontend apps

Better maintainability



---

2️⃣ Directives (Conditional Query Execution)

GraphQL provides built-in directives:

@include

@skip


Example

query GetUser($withEmail: Boolean!) {
  getUser(id: "1") {
    name
    email @include(if: $withEmail)
  }
}

If $withEmail = false, email will not be returned.

You can also create custom directives in server-side schema.


---

3️⃣ Interfaces (Polymorphism)

Interfaces define common fields for multiple types.

Example

interface Character {
  id: ID!
  name: String!
}

type Human implements Character {
  id: ID!
  name: String!
  totalCredits: Int
}

type Droid implements Character {
  id: ID!
  name: String!
  primaryFunction: String
}

type Query {
  character(id: ID!): Character
}

Query with Inline Fragments

query {
  character(id: "1") {
    name
    ... on Human {
      totalCredits
    }
    ... on Droid {
      primaryFunction
    }
  }
}

Resolver Type Resolution

Character: {
  __resolveType(obj) {
    if (obj.totalCredits) return "Human";
    if (obj.primaryFunction) return "Droid";
    return null;
  }
}


---

4️⃣ Unions (Multiple Possible Types)

Similar to interfaces but without shared fields.

union SearchResult = User | Post

type Query {
  search(text: String!): [SearchResult]
}

Query

query {
  search(text: "GraphQL") {
    ... on User {
      name
    }
    ... on Post {
      title
    }
  }
}


---

5️⃣ Enums

Enums restrict allowed values.

enum Role {
  ADMIN
  USER
  GUEST
}

type User {
  id: ID!
  role: Role!
}

Mutation example:

mutation {
  createUser(name: "John", role: ADMIN) {
    id
    role
  }
}


---

6️⃣ Subscriptions (Real-time Data)

Subscriptions allow real-time updates using WebSockets.

Unlike HTTP-based Query/Mutation, subscriptions require WebSocket.

Popular implementations:

graphql-ws

Apollo Server subscriptions


Schema

type Subscription {
  userCreated: User
}

Subscription Query

subscription {
  userCreated {
    id
    name
  }
}

Resolver Example (Node.js)

const { PubSub } = require('graphql-subscriptions');
const pubsub = new PubSub();

const resolvers = {
  Subscription: {
    userCreated: {
      subscribe: () => pubsub.asyncIterator(['USER_CREATED'])
    }
  }
};


---

7️⃣ Context (Authentication & Authorization)

Context is passed to every resolver.

Used for:

Auth

DB connections

User session


Example:

const server = new ApolloServer({
  typeDefs,
  resolvers,
  context: ({ req }) => {
    const token = req.headers.authorization;
    const user = verifyToken(token);
    return { user };
  }
});

Resolver usage:

getUser: (parent, args, context) => {
  if (!context.user) throw new Error("Unauthorized");
}


---

8️⃣ Custom Scalars

GraphQL supports custom types like Date.

scalar Date

Resolver:

const { GraphQLScalarType, Kind } = require('graphql');

Date: new GraphQLScalarType({
  name: 'Date',
  serialize(value) {
    return value.toISOString();
  },
  parseValue(value) {
    return new Date(value);
  },
  parseLiteral(ast) {
    if (ast.kind === Kind.STRING) {
      return new Date(ast.value);
    }
  }
})


---

9️⃣ Error Handling

GraphQL always returns HTTP 200 but includes errors in response.

{
  "data": null,
  "errors": [
    {
      "message": "Unauthorized"
    }
  ]
}

Best Practice:

Throw specific errors

Use error extensions


throw new GraphQLError("Forbidden", {
  extensions: { code: "FORBIDDEN" }
});


---

🔟 Query Depth & Complexity Limiting

To prevent abuse:

Limit query depth

Limit query complexity

Timeout long-running queries


Libraries:

graphql-depth-limit

graphql-query-complexity


Example:

const depthLimit = require('graphql-depth-limit');

validationRules: [depthLimit(5)]


