🏗 1️⃣ High-Level GraphQL Architecture Overview

At scale, a production-ready GraphQL system typically looks like this:

Clients (Web / Mobile / Admin)
        ↓
CDN / Edge Cache
        ↓
GraphQL Gateway (Federation Layer)
        ↓
-------------------------------
|  User Service (GraphQL)     |
|  Product Service (GraphQL)  |
|  Order Service (GraphQL)    |
|  Payment Service (GraphQL)  |
-------------------------------
        ↓
Databases / Caches / External APIs

Now let’s break down each layer.


---

🌍 2️⃣ Client Layer

Clients:

Web apps (React, Next.js)

Mobile apps

Admin dashboards


Best practices:

Use persisted queries

Enable query batching

Normalize cache on client (Apollo/Relay)


Why? GraphQL allows clients to fetch exactly what they need — reducing overfetching and underfetching.


---

🚀 3️⃣ CDN / Edge Layer

GraphQL is usually POST-based, so caching is tricky.

Solutions:

✅ Persisted Queries + GET

Client sends query hash

CDN caches response

Faster global performance


✅ Gzip / Brotli Compression

Reduces payload size.

This layer improves:

Latency

Scalability

Global performance



